Analyzing the Red Wine Data Set by Jon Baker

Introducing the Red Wine Data Set

This data set looks at over 1,000 red wines. It looks like there are 13 variables to look at, with one of them being a primary key. I notice that some variables operate on different orders of magnitude than others.

Here are some charts looking at all of the variables in the data set.

These visualizations were created in order to get a feel for the variables. We can see that the Quality of Red Wines chart is based on integers, not real numbers. Fixed Acidity, Density, Volatile Acidity and pH have the most normal-looking curves out of the bunch. Many of these charts have tails on the right, including the Sulfur Dioxide charts, Sulphates chart, Alcohol chart and especially the Residual Sugar and Chlorides charts.

Here is a close-up view of alcohol content. This is an important feature in wines. We can see the mean is around 10.5 % or so. It will be interesting to look this over in the multivariate analysis, as it is correlated with quality.

This is a histogram of sulfate content in red wines. You can see here that the mean is around .7 or so. This will also be interesting in the multivariate analysis, as it is correlated with quality.

Citric Acid is positively correlated with the quality of red wines. We can see here that the mean is around 0.25, and this is not a normal histogram at all, but an entirely different shape.

It will be interesting to look at a multivariate analysis of this chart with regards to quality.

Volatile Acidity is important, as we find out later, because it is negatively associated with red wine quality. Here, we can see the mean is around 0.5 .

This looks like a normal curve with a right tail. It will be interesting to look at a multivariate analysis of this chart with regards to quality.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

This data set is structured with 11 numeric variables and 1 categorical variable (quality). There is also the primary key in a column by itself. To be more specific, all of the variables except for quality are numeric and real. However, the variable for quality is numeric and an integer. I will have to transform it, but it should work very well.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The categorical variable called quality could be useful when doing a multivariate analysis. Density, pH, sulphites and alcohol content are tracked. In addition, fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide are tracked.

I am not sure what others would be interested in, but I am interested in how acids affect things like pH and density. I already know that more acid means less pH, but I would like to see it in action with the data. I want to check and see if more citric acid makes more fixed acidity.

Others might be interested in how alcohol content, sulfates, residual sugars, citric acid and even pH affect the quality rating. So we will look into that as well.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I really like how quality is an integer. This makes it a candidate for helping out with multivariate analysis.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I did not create any new variables.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Two of the variables, residual sugar and chlorides, have long tails on the right and I would prefer to chop those off if I were to use those graphs in a presentation.

Here, we can see that fixed acidity is negatively correlated with volatile acidity and positively correlated with volatile acidity. Acidity in general seems to be correlated with density, and also negatively correlated with pH.

What is most correlated with quality? Well, that would be alcohol content, citric acid and sulfates. In addition, volatile acidity is associated with poor quality.

Bivarate Plots

### Descriptions of the scatterplots

It looks like citric acid is associated with fixed acidity, with a correlation of .6717 . Fixed acidity is also positively correlated with density, with a correlation value of .6680 .

What about citric acid vs.volatile acidity? We notice a negative correlation here of -.5525, which gives us a clue to the nature of volatile acidity - it probably comes from something other than citric acid.

When I mapped variables such as alcohol content, residual sugar, and citric acid vs.quality, I do not know how to read these charts. I think there was an issue because quality is an integer. However, we will look at these charts again in the section on multivariate analysis.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

I showed a scatterplot of fixed acidity vs.citric acid to see if they were correlated, and they were, in a positive manner. Similarly, fixed acidity was positively correlated with density.

These were scientific experiments to see if increasing citric acid increased fixed acidity. I made the hypothesis that it would. In addition, I wanted to see if acids were denser than neutral substances, in general.

I noticed that pH tends to lower the more acids are added, which makes sense.

I did not see many patterns in the sulfates, residual sugars, pH and citric acid vs.quality scatterplots.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Quality was most highly correlated with sulfates and alcohol content.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Fixed Acidity vs.Density was one of the strongest relationships I found, which is quite interesting! Could there be something to this?

In addition, there were other high correlations, like sulfates vs.total sulfur dioxide and fixed acidity vs.citric acid that were strong. There was also a strong relationship between pH and fixed acidity, which makes sense as the more acidic something is, the lower its pH, by law.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

I wanted to try looking at sulfates and alcohol content in relation to quality one more time with a multivariate analysis. These two things were the most correlated with quality, after all.

In the graphs produced you can look at the alcohol and phosphate distributions for different quality ratings.

The scatterplot featuring sulfates vs.alcohol content is there as well, with quality layered on as different colors.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

I was surprised that mid-quality (5) wines were so closely packed around their mean sulfate content and alcohol content. I am also surprised that alcohol and sulfates are hardly correlated at all! This means that they are separate, independent features that could predict quality of wines in an algorithm.

Reflection

I found out that a multivariate analysis was better for exploring the relationship between things such as sulfates vs.quality than a scatterplot. I could not get a feel for those scatterplots that I made earlier in the exploration.

I was personally interested in using this data set to learn a bit about chemistry and physics, while I think others might be interested in using it to learn what kinds of wines have a high quality rating. So I did a bit of both in the exploration.

The first two scatterplots I made, citric acid vs.fixed acidity and fixed acidity vs.density went well. In addition, the mass-production of correlation values as well as univariate charts went very well. Those gave a decent overview of the data, along with the data summary. I thought the multivariate analysis went well, but it is my first time doing one, and I am not sure.

I was surprised at the relationship between acidity and density. In the future, I would like to do more multivariate analysis with the quality variable.
